# ReScript Rules

## Module & Naming Conventions
- **PascalCase** for module files: `PaymentList.res`, `APIUtils.res`
- **camelCase** for values and functions: `let fetchPayments`, `let handleSubmit`
- Every significant `.res` module should have a `.resi` interface file

## React Components
- Always use `@react.component` decorator on component `let make`
- JSX v4 classic mode — use `React.string`, `React.int`, `React.null`
- Props are labeled arguments: `(~title: string, ~onClose: unit => unit)`

```rescript
@react.component
let make = (~title: string, ~onClose: unit => unit) => {
  <div className="flex flex-col gap-4">
    <p> {title->React.string} </p>
    <button onClick={_ => onClose()}> {"Close"->React.string} </button>
  </div>
}
```

## Pattern Matching
- Must be **exhaustive** — the compiler enforces this
- Never use a catch-all `_` when variants can be listed explicitly

## Standard Library
- `RescriptCore` is **globally opened** via `-open RescriptCore` in `bsc-flags`
- Use `Array.map`, `Option.getOr`, `Dict.get`, `String.startsWith` directly
- **Never** add `open RescriptCore` inside a module — it is redundant
- Belt is available but prefer RescriptCore for new code

## Types
- Use records over JS object literals wherever possible
- Variant types for domain states (not string constants)
- Prefer explicit type annotations at module boundaries

## JS Interop
- JS nullable → `Js.Nullable.toOption`
- Module bindings: `@module("pkg") @val external name: type = "export"`
- `%raw` is an escape hatch — use only at JS interop boundaries, never for business logic

## Prohibited
- No TypeScript (`.ts`/`.tsx`) in `src/`
- No JS object literals where records work
- No editing `.res.js` compiled output directly
